properties.areaDesc: Southern Erie
properties.headline: Lake Effect Snow Warning issued November 25 at 9:48PM EST until November 27 at 7:00AM EST by NWS Cleveland OH
properties.description:
* WHAT...Heavy lake effect snow expected. Total snow accumulations
of 6 to 11 inches. Winds gusting 35 to 40 mph.

* WHERE...Southern Erie county.

* WHEN...From 1 AM Friday to 7 AM EST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Patchy blowing snow
could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous
conditions could impact the morning or evening commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Highest snowfall accumulations are expected
in the eastern half of the county. The greatest snowfall rates
are expected Friday morning, with one inch per hour rates
possible. This will cause hazardous travel conditions,
particularly along the I-90 and I-86 corridors.

your vehicle in case of an emergency.

properties.areaDesc: Southeast Webster; Northwest Pocahontas; Southeast Randolph
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 9:09PM EST by NWS Charleston WV
properties.description:
Temperatures dropping below freezing overnight will result in a
changeover from rain to snow showers, with light snow
accumulations beginning during the early morning hours Friday.
Snow accumulations can range from one to as much as three inches
through Friday morning, before the snow showers taper off to snow
flurries Friday afternoon.

Conditions can deteriorate rapidly in winter weather situations.
Be prepared for a sudden decrease in visibility and quick
accumulation on roadways. Moisture underneath the snow can freeze.
Slow down and allow extra time when traveling.

Northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph, with gusts of 40 to 45 mph, will
further reduce visibility, could cause minor tree damage, blow
unsecured objects around and create a further hazard for high
profile vehicles in a cross wind. Secure loose objects and use
caution when traveling.

These strong winds, with temperatures in the upper teens to lower
20s, will combine to cause wind chill indices in the single
digits, making outdoor exposure dangerous at times. Wear
protective winter clothing.

properties.areaDesc: Orleans; Essex; Lamoille; Caledonia; Washington
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 8:03PM EST by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
An area of light mixed precipitation will affect north central and
northeastern Vermont later this evening, generally from 9 pm to 1
am. During this period a mix of light rain, light snow and light
freezing rain will be possible. While any ice accumulations will
be negligible, a light glaze will be possible on area roads where
pavement temperatures are near to slightly below freezing. Please
exercise caution this evening if traveling.
properties.instruction:
Light freezing rain or drizzle may quickly coat roadways with a
thin layer of ice that may be undetectable. Please use extreme
caution...especially on bridges...overpasses and around curves.
Allow plenty of stopping distance and avoid braking suddenly.

NWSheadline: Areas of light freezing rain or freezing drizzle possible this evening

properties.areaDesc: Clallam, WA
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued November 25 at 4:02PM PST by NWS Seattle WA
properties.description:
Wet frontal systems with a high snow levels will bring periods of
heavy rain to the Olympics. This will result in rising rivers
across the area and an enhanced risk of landslides.

The first weather system will move through the area this afternoon
and tonight. Rivers draining out of the Olympics will need to be
watched for a chance of flooding.

A second frontal system will arrive Saturday night and Sunday with
another round of heavy rain possible in the mountains.

There is a chance that a third wet frontal system will reach the
area by the middle of next week.

Please monitor the latest river forecasts from the National Weather
Service for additional information.

* WHERE...A portion of west central Washington, including the
following areas, King and Snohomish.

* WHEN...From late tonight through Saturday morning.

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Heavy rain in the Cascades will cause sharp rises on area
rivers tonight. Minor flooding is possible Friday and Friday
night.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:

Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.

properties.description:

Warning, which is in effect from 10 AM to 5 PM MST Friday.

* AFFECTED AREA...Fire weather zone 310 and 313.

* WIND...West winds 20 to 25 mph with gusts to 35 to 40 mph.

* HUMIDITY...8 to 13 percent.

* IMPACTS...any fires that develop will likely spread rapidly.

properties.instruction:

are either occurring now....or will shortly. A combination of
strong winds...low relative humidity...and warm temperatures can
contribute to extreme fire behavior.

properties.areaDesc: Clallam, WA; King, WA; Skagit, WA; Snohomish, WA
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued November 25 at 2:26PM PST by NWS Seattle WA
properties.description:
Wet frontal systems with a high snow levels will bring periods of
heavy rain to the mountains. This will result in rising rivers
across the area and an enhanced risk of landslides.

The first weather system will move through the area this afternoon
and
tonight. Rivers draining out of the Olympics and the central and
northern Cascades will need to be watched for a chance of flooding.

A second frontal system will arrive Saturday night and Sunday with
another round of heavy rain possible in the mountains.

There is a chance that a third wet frontal system will reach the
area by the middle of next week.

Please monitor the latest river forecasts from the National Weather
Service for additional information.

properties.description:

* WHERE...Antelope Valley.

* WHEN...From 2 AM to 9 AM PST Friday.

unprotected pets or livestock.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 4:51PM EST by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
Significant drying and gusty winds in the wake of a cold front
will lead to an increased risk of fires growing out of control on
Friday. With relative humidity likely to drop below 30 percent and
northwest winds expected to gust above 20 mph, these conditions
will allow fires to spread more quickly. Outdoor burning is
discouraged.

Please refer to your local burn permitting authorities on whether
you can burn on Friday. If you do burn, use extreme caution since
fires can quickly get out of hand under these conditions.

Rain showers will change to snow showers across the area after 1
am tonight and linger into Friday morning in the far eastern
parts of eastern Kentucky. While most places will see a dusting or
less of accumulation, in the higher terrain above 2000 feet up to
an inch of accumulation will occur. This could lead to slick road
conditions at times in the highest elevations through Friday
morning. Motorists are urged to slow down and use caution while
traveling in the higher terrain later tonight and into Friday
morning.

NWSheadline: Light Snow Accumulations Possible Above 2000 Feet Tonight

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 4:13PM EST by NWS Raleigh NC
properties.description:
Rapid drying and gusty winds behind a cold front will lead to an
increased risk for rapid fire growth Friday afternoon and early
evening.

Outdoor burning is discouraged. Please refer to your local burn
permitting authority on whether you can burn. If you do burn, use
extreme caution and ensure fire suppression equipment is readily
available.

NWSheadline: INCREASED FIRE DANGER FRIDAY

properties.areaDesc: Surry; Stokes; Rockingham; Caswell; Wilkes; Yadkin
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 4:08PM EST by NWS Blacksburg VA
properties.description:
There is an increased threat of fires growing out of control on
Friday due to a combination of low humidity expected to fall
below 30 percent, northwest winds gusting above 20 mph, and dry
fuels. These conditions will make it possible for fire to spread
quickly.

Outdoor burning is strongly discouraged during this time. Please
refer to your local burn permitting authority on whether you can
burn. If you do burn, use extreme caution and ensure fire
suppression equipment is readily available.

NWSheadline: INCREASED FIRE DANGER IS EXPECTED FOR FRIDAY FROM 11 AM EST UNTIL 6 PM EST

properties.areaDesc: Southwest
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued November 25 at 5:01PM AST until November 28 at 6:00AM AST by NWS San Juan PR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Dangerous rip currents expected due to breaking waves of
up to 7 feet.

* WHERE...Southwestern beaches of Puerto Rico.

* WHEN...Through late Saturday night.

* IMPACTS...Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and
localized beach erosion. Rip currents can sweep even the best
swimmers away from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

NWSheadline: HIGH RIP CURRENT RISK IN EFFECT THROUGH LATE SATURDAY NIGHT

properties.areaDesc: St.Thomas...St. John.. and Adjacent Islands

properties.description:

to 12 feet are expected. For the High Rip Current Risk,
dangerous rip currents are expected.

* WHERE...Beaches of Saint Thomas and Saint John.

* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, from 6 AM Friday to 8 AM
AST Saturday. For the High Rip Current Risk, through Sunday
afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.description:

20 to 30 mph, and relative humidity values around 30 to 40% will
result in an increased risk for rapid fire growth Friday afternoon.

Outdoor burning is discouraged. Please refer to your local burn
permitting authority on whether you can burn. If you do burn, use
extreme caution and ensure fire suppression equipment is readily
available.

NWSheadline: INCREASED FIRE DANGER FRIDAY AFTERNOON

properties.areaDesc: Robeson; Bladen; Columbus; Inland Pender; Coastal Pender; Inland New Hanover; Coastal New Hanover; Inland Brunswick; Coastal Brunswick
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 3:57PM EST by NWS Wilmington NC
properties.description:
A cold frontal passage accompanied by a few showers early
Friday morning will be quickly followed by a dry airmass with
afternoon relative humidities dropping to and below 30 percent.
Gusty W to NW winds will accompany the drier air, with sustained
10 to 20 mph speeds along with frequent gusts around 25 mph.
Marginally low fuel moistures will further dry during Friday
afternoon. Winds will diminish-some by sunset Friday along with
recovering relative humidities.
properties.instruction:
Please refer to your local burn permitting authorities on whether
you can burn during Friday. If you do, you are advised to use
extreme caution since fires can quickly get out of control under
these conditions.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Sub-freezing temperatures as low as 30 degrees possible.

* WHERE...Portions of south central and southwest Alabama,
northwest Florida and southeast Mississippi.

* WHEN...From late Friday night through Saturday morning.

* IMPACTS...Frost and freeze conditions could kill crops, other
sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.
properties.instruction:
Take steps now to protect tender plants from the cold. To prevent
freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes they should
be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those that have
in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover above-
ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 3:52PM EST by NWS Wakefield VA
properties.description:
The combination of northwest winds of 15 to 20 mph, with gusts to
30 mph, a drying airmass and fuels will result in an increased
fire danger over northeast North Carolina Friday afternoon.
Minimum relative humidity values will fall to between 30 and 35
percent during the afternoon hours.

ignition source...including machinery... cigarettes...and matches.
Be sure to properly discard all smoking materials. Any dry grasses
and tree litter that ignite will have the potential to spread
quickly.

properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued November 25 at 10:40AM PST by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
properties.description:
The Ventura County Air Pollution Control District has issued an Air
Quality Alert due to blowing dust. This Air Quality Alert is in
effect until 9 AM PST Friday.

Exposure to particle pollution can cause serious health problems,
aggravate lung disease, cause asthma attacks and acute bronchitis,
and increase risk of respiratory infections. Residents are advised to
use caution as conditions warrant. People with heart or lung diseases
should follow their doctors advice for dealing with episodes of
unhealthy air quality. Additionally, people with respiratory or heart
disease, older adults, and children should avoid prolonged exposure,
strenuous activities or heavy exertion as conditions dictate.

For the additional information, call the Ventura County Air
Pollution Control District at 805.662.6960, visit vcapcd.org, or
follow VCAPCD on Twitter (@vcapcd).

detected from the Katmai volcano. Even though Katmai erupted in
1912, from time to time when wind conditions line up, ash becomes
airborne. Northerly winds will transport trace amounts of ashfall
over Shelikof Strait and portions of Kodiak. The resuspended ash
will diminish as the winds decrease tonight.

portions of Kodiak. The resuspended ash will diminish as the winds
decrease tonight.

NWSheadline: GALE WARNING TONIGHT

properties.areaDesc: Alaska Peninsula; Eastern Aleutians; Pribilof Islands
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 3:45AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
Snow showers and gusty northwesterly winds are expected to
continue across the Alaska Peninsula, Pribilofs, and Eastern
Aleutians through this evening. Arctic air continues to move off
the Alaska mainland and over the relatively warm water of the
Bering. Thus, the atmosphere will continue to be moistened and
contribute to snow shower development through this evening as the
pattern remains stagnant.

Wind gusts ranging from 30 to 40 mph this morning will slowly
subside to 20 to 30 mph by this evening. As a result, any falling
snow combined with the gusty winds could reduce visibility to as
low as one half mile at times. Locations that continue to be
impacted by these adverse conditions include False Pass, Port
Heiden, Cold Bay, Dutch Harbor, and Saint Paul.

Widespread snow shower activity throughout the morning and into
the afternoon will become more isolated in nature during the
evening.

NWSheadline: OCCASIONALLY HEAVY SNOW SHOWERS AND STRONG GUSTY WINDS EXPECTED TO CONTINUE THROUGH THIS EVENING ACROSS THE EASTERN BERING

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued November 25 at 4:40AM PST by NWS Seattle WA
properties.description:
Rainfall of 3 to 8 inches over the past two weeks has increased soil
moisture levels across western Washington. Heavy rainfall of 1 to 3
inches is expected across the lowlands through Friday, with highest
amounts along the coast and near the west slopes of the Olympics and
Cascades. This amount of rain will put extra pressure on soil
instability, leading to an increased threat of landslides.

For more information about current conditions, visit
www.weather.gov/seattle, select Hydrology, and then scroll down
for the links to the landslide information pages.

For more information on landslides, visit the website for the
Washington State Department of Natural Resources landslide
geologic hazards at: http://bit.ly/2mtA3wn

properties.headline: Winter Storm Watch issued November 25 at 2:59AM EST until November 27 at 4:00PM EST by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
* WHAT...Heavy snow possible. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 10
inches possible. Locally higher amounts up to a foot possible at
higher elevations of the northern Greens.

* WHERE...Portions of the Greens in Vermont, northern Vermont,
and northern New York.

* WHEN...From Friday morning through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Areas of blowing snow
could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous conditions
could impact the Friday evening commute and post holiday travel
plans.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...After a cold front crosses the region
Friday morning, rain or a wintry mix of precipitation will
transition to all snow Friday afternoon and continue through
Saturday afternoon, particularly in upslope regions of the
northern Greens and Adirondacks. Friday night into Saturday,
wind gusts out of the northwest up to 25 to 35 mph are expected,
which could result in areas of blowing snow from the fresh snow.
Hazardous travel is possible, particularly along gap roads and
untreated surfaces.
properties.instruction: Monitor the latest forecasts for updates on this situation.

* WHEN...6 PM this Evening to Midnight Friday.

and hypothermia can occur if precautions are not taken.

properties.description:

inches.

* WHERE...Juneau Borough and Northern Admiralty Island.

* WHEN...From midnight Thursday night to 6 AM AKST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. The hazardous
conditions could impact the morning or evening commute. It could
also impact holiday travel.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Expect snow to arrive in showers. Heavier
showers will occasionally produce snow squalls with low
visibility and high rates of accumulation followed by periods of
little to snow snow and good visibility. Therefore, amounts will
be highly variable from time to time and from neighborhood to
neighborhood.

For the latest road conditions call 5 1 1 or visit
511.alaska.gov.

properties.areaDesc: South Central Oregon Coast; Curry County Coast
properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued November 24 at 3:18PM PST until November 25 at 9:00PM PST by NWS Medford OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Higher threat for sneaker waves expected.

* WHERE...Beaches along the southern Oregon Coast, including the
beaches of Douglas, Coos and Curry Counties.

* WHEN...From late Thursday morning through Thursday evening.

* IMPACTS...Even during calm conditions, sneaker waves can sweep
up the beach without warning and knock unsuspecting people
over and pull them out to sea. Shock and hypothermia can occur
quickly in the cold Pacific waters. In addition, logs and
other debris can be lifted and carried by the waves, crushing
or entrapping unsuspecting victims underneath.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The sneaker wave threat is higher
Thursday afternoon with a high tide around 3 pm. The waves are
not especially large, generally in the 4-6 foot range with
periods of 16-18 seconds, but these waves could have the
ability to run farther up the beach than usual.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr
properties.instruction: Remain out of the water to avoid hazardous swimming conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Ventura County Coast; Ventura County Interior Valleys; Ventura County Coastal Valleys; Santa Clarita Valley; Los Angeles County San Fernando Valley
properties.headline: Red Flag Warning issued November 24 at 10:20AM PST until November 26 at 6:00PM PST by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
properties.description:
* Winds...Northeast 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 50 mph during the
peak tonight through early Thursday afternoon, otherwise
northeast 15 to 25 mph with gusts to 40 mph. Isolated gusts to
65 mph possible in the hills Thursday morning.

* Relative Humidity...As low as 8 and 15 percent today, and 2 to
10 percent on Thursday and Friday. Very poor to no overnight
recoveries.

* Impacts...If fire ignition occurs, conditions will be
favorable for rapid fire spread, long range spotting, and
extreme fire behavior which would threaten life and property.
properties.instruction:
A Red Flag Warning means that critical fire weather conditions
are either occurring now....or will shortly. A combination of
strong winds and low relative humidity can contribute to extreme
fire behavior. Use extreme caution with potential fire ignition
sources.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Higher threat for sneaker waves expected.

* WHERE...In Washington, South Washington Coast. In Oregon,
North Oregon Coast and Central Oregon Coast.

* WHEN...From Thursday morning through Friday evening.

* IMPACTS...Sneaker waves can suddenly knock people off of their
feet and quickly pull them into the frigid ocean, which may lead
to serious injury or drowning.

Immersion in cold water can cause cold water paralysis within
minutes, further impairing an individual's ability to escape.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High tide occurring Thursday afternoon may
bring the period of highest threat, especially over the WA
coasts where the higher seas will be occurring.
properties.instruction: Remain out of the water to avoid hazardous swimming conditions.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:

float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: South Central Oregon Coast; Curry County Coast
properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued November 23 at 10:56AM PST until November 25 at 9:00PM PST by NWS Medford OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Higher threat for sneaker waves expected.

* WHERE...Beaches along the southern Oregon Coast, including the
beaches of Douglas, Coos and Curry Counties.

* WHEN...From late Thursday morning through Thursday evening.

* IMPACTS...Even during calm conditions, sneaker waves can sweep
up the beach without warning and knock unsuspecting people
over and pull them out to sea. Shock and hypothermia can occur
quickly in the cold Pacific waters. In addition, logs and
other debris can be lifted and carried by the waves, crushing
or entrapping unsuspecting victims underneath.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The sneaker wave threat is higher Thursday
afternoon with a high tide around 3 pm. The waves are not
especially large, generally in the 3-5 foot range with periods
of 16-18 seconds, but these waves could have the ability to run
farther up the beach than usual.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr
properties.instruction:
Use extreme caution along the beaches and keep your distance from
the ocean. NEVER turn your back on the ocean!

Remain out of the water and avoid areas of the beach with excess
debris.

NWSheadline: BEACH HAZARDS STATEMENT IN EFFECT FROM LATE THURSDAY MORNING THROUGH THURSDAY EVENING

properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Los Angeles/Oxnard has issued a
Red Flag Warning FOR GUSTY NORTHEAST WINDS AND VERY LOW RELATIVE
HUMIDITY, which is in effect from 10 AM Wednesday to 6
PM PST Friday. The Fire Weather Watch is no longer in effect.

* Winds...Northeast 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 50 mph. Isolated
gusts up to 60 mph Wednesday afternoon through Thursday morning.

* Relative Humidity...lowering to between 10 and 15 percent on
Wednesday then to as low as 2 to 8 percent on Thursday and Friday.
